'''Oda Chausuyama Kofun''' (太田茶臼山古墳) is a [[:en:Zenpokoenfun|Zenpokoenfun]] located in [[:en:Ibaraki, Osaka|Ibaraki, Osaka]], Osaka Prefecture, Oda. It is the largest tumulus in northern Osaka and Ranks as the 21st largest in Japan.

Though the actual interred individual is unknown, the [[:en:Imperial Household Agency|Imperial Household Agency]] designates it as "Mishima Aino Mausoleum," attributed to [[:en:Emperor Keitai|Emperor Keitai]].

== Overview ==

The tumulus was constructed on the {{ill|Tonda Plateau|ja|富田台地|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tonda Plateau|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} near the right bank of the [[:en:Yodo River|Yodo River]]. Current management falls under the jurisdiction of the Imperial Household Agency, which recognizes it as Emperor Keitai's mausoleum. Excavations outside the surrounding moat have been conducted by the Osaka Prefectural and Ibaraki City Boards of Education in 1972 and 1988. The Imperial Household Agency's Sho-Ryo Division also carried out a survey at the mound's base in 2002.<ref name="ExplanationBoard"/>

The tumulus features a keyhole type, with the front mound oriented south. It measures 226 meters in total length, making it the largest in northern Osaka. Its moat and embankments encircle the mound in a shield type, with figurative and cylindrical [[:en:Haniwa|haniwa]] excavated from its surroundings. Production of these haniwa has been linked to the {{ill|Shinike Haniwa Production Site|ja|史跡新池ハニワ工場公園|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinike Haniwa Production Site|qq=}} in Takatsuki.<ref>{{Harvid|新修茨木市史 第7巻 史料編 考古|2014|pp=293-297}}</ref> Other small tombs, believed to be satellite mounds, are located nearby.

== Burial Individual ==

The actual burial individual is unknown, but the Imperial Household Agency attributes the tumulus to Emperor Keitai. Some scholars argue that [[:en:Imashirozuka Kofun|Imashirozuka Kofun]] (Takatsuki, Osaka Prefecture) better matches historical records and Emperor Keitai's era.<ref>{{Harvid|新修茨木市史 第1巻 通史|2012|pp=381-389}}</ref>

== Excavated Items ==

burial goods such as cylindrical haniwa, figurative haniwa, and roof tiles have been unearthed. These findings are stored and displayed at the {{ill|Ibaraki Municipal Museum|ja|茨木市立文化財資料館|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ibaraki Municipal Museum|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}.

== Cultural Importance ==

The surrounding moat is Historic Site1 as part of a national historic site, and the tumulus holds significant cultural value as a testament to the burial practices and social structures of 5th-century Japan.

== References ==
{{Reflist}}

== Related Facilities ==
